==English==

===Etymology===
From Anglo-Saxon '''[[abbod]]''', '''[[abbad]]''', from  Latin '''[[abbas]]''', '''[[abbatis]]''', from Greek '''[[&#7936;&beta;&beta;&alpha;&#834;&#962;]]''', from [[Syriac]] '''[[abb&#257;]]''',  ''father''. Cf. [[abba]], [[abbé]].

===Pronunciation===
* ([[RP]]) [[IPA]]: /ˈæbət/

===Noun===
{{en-noun-reg}}

# The superior or head of an [[abbey]] or [[monastery]].
#:''The newly appointed '''abbot''' decided to take a tour of the abbey with the cardinal's emissary.''
# One of a class of bishops whose sees were formerly abbeys. ''"Encyclopedia Britannica"''

